   (Message) The program allocates an integer with `new`, then decrements the
   pointer, pointing to before the allocated memory. When attempting to delete
   `n`, it deletes memory it doesn't own, producing undefined behavior. After
   deletion, `doSomething` uses the dangling pointer, leading to a use-after-
   free when dereferencing a possibly invalid memory location.
   
   ROOT CAUSE: `program.cpp:11` - Decrementing the pointer `n` before it's
   passed to `delete` results in undefined behavior because `delete` is called
   on a non-allocated memory region. Consequently, when `doSomething` is invoked
   with `n`, the dereferencing operates on invalid memory, causing a
   segmentation fault.
   
   LOCAL FIX: Avoid modifying the pointer before deletion.
   ```cpp
   int * n = new int(100);
   // n--; // Remove or relocate n-- to maintain semantics
   delete n;
   ```
   
   GLOBAL FIX: Implement rigorous memory handling through smart pointers (like
   `std::unique_ptr`) to manage object lifetimes automatically, eliminating
   risks of manual pointer manipulation and incorrect deallocation.
